Supervised Learning Regression Project: Cars4U¶

Submitted by: Larry Weatherford on June 9, 2023

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian Market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholes in this market.

In 2018-19, while new car sales were recorded at 3.6 million units, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold. There is a slowdown in new car sales and that could mean that the demand is shifting towards the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones. Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts which come into play only in the last stage of the customer journey), used cars are very different beasts with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.

As a senior data scientist at Cars4U, you have to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing. For example, if the business knows the market price, it will never sell anything below it.

Objective¶

To explore and visualize the dataset, build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars, and generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used cars sold in different locations. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • S.No.: Serial number
  • Name: Name of the car which includes brand name and model name
  • Location: Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)
  • Year: Manufacturing year of the car
  • Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in km
  • Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  • Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)
  • Owner_Type: Type of ownership
  • Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  • Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC
  • Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  • Seats: The number of seats in the car
  • New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh = 100,000 INR)
  • Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

# Histogram and Boxplot for univarient features
def histbox(df, column, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Histogram and Boxplot 

    df: dataframe
    column: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid = 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=df, x=column, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True, color="orange"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=column, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=column, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist.axvline(
        df[column].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist.axvline(df[column].median(), color="blue", linestyle="-")
    ax_hist.set_title(column, fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')  # Set title with underline
    ax_hist.set_xlabel(column, fontsize=15)  # Set xlabel

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()  # show the plot

# Dropping the S.No. Columns as it provides no value to us
cars.drop("S.No.", axis=1, inplace=True)

# Extract Brand and Model info from Name column and place into 2 new columns
cars['Name'] = cars['Name'].str.replace('Land Rover', 'Land-Rover')
cars['Brand'] = cars['Name'].str.split(' ', n=1, expand=True)[0].astype('category') 
cars['Model'] = cars['Name'].str.split(' ', n=1, expand=True)[1].astype('category') 
cars.drop(['Name'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# Strip out non-numeric characters from Mileage column and covert column to float
cars['Mileage'] = cars['Mileage'].str.replace(r'\D', '', regex=True)
cars['Mileage'] = cars['Mileage'].astype(float)

# Strip out non-numeric characters from Power column and covert column to float
cars['Power'] = cars['Power'].str.replace(r'\D', '', regex=True)
cars['Power'] = cars['Power'].astype(float)

# Strip out non-numeric characters from Engine column and covert column to float
cars['Engine'] = cars['Engine'].str.replace(r'\D', '', regex=True)
cars['Engine'] = cars['Engine'].astype(float)

histbox(cars, 'Power',figsize=(9, 5))

Observations:

  1. Power has outliers we need to evaluate.
  2. It has 175 missing values that we will impute using the median since the data is right skewed.
  3. For some reason the Power is not importing correctly into the dataset. By exporting the data into Excel I could see that the bhp powers are off by orders of magnitude. To correct this data we use this approach: If Power >=5000 divide by 100 else if Power >=500 and <= 5000 divide by 10 This should correct most of the data and bring it in line with realistic bhp
In [646]:
# Replace the missing values in the "Power" column with the median
cars['Power'].fillna(cars['Power'].median(), inplace=True)
In [647]:
# Correctly the order of magnitude issues with the Power data
cars.loc[cars['Power'] >= 5000, 'Power'] = cars.loc[cars['Power'] >= 5000, 'Power'] / 100
cars.loc[(cars['Power'] >= 500) & (cars['Power'] < 5000), 'Power'] = cars.loc[(cars['Power'] >= 500) & (cars['Power'] < 5000), 'Power'] / 10

# There are 5 car models that have incorrect bhp.  After verifing the correct bhp these car models were updated as shown below.
cars.loc[cars['Power'] == 473, 'Power'] = 47  #Car Model Maruti Alto 800 LXI
cars.loc[cars['Power'] == 463, 'Power'] = 46  #Car Model Maruti Alto LXi
cars.loc[cars['Power'] == 403, 'Power'] = 40  #Car Model Maruti Alto 800 2016-2019 CNG LXI
cars.loc[cars['Power'] == 375, 'Power'] = 38  #Car Model Tata Nano Twist XT
cars.loc[cars['Power'] == 342, 'Power'] = 34  #Car Model Maruti Omni E

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. How is the pricing of used cars distributed?
  2. What is the market share of different brands in the used car market?
  3. What is the market share of different types of fuels in the used car market?
  4. How does the prices of used cars vary by car brand?
  5. How does the prices of used cars vary by location?
  6. What are the attributes that have a strong correlation with the price of used cars?

# 6. What are the attributes that have a strong correlation with the price of used cars? 
# We will use a heatmap to show all the numeric correlations between features

# Select only the numeric columns
numeric_cols = cars.select_dtypes(include='number')

# Calculate the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = numeric_cols.corr()

# Create a heatmap

Model Building Function for Linear Regression¶

Define a linear regression function that accepts a dataframe, target_variable and model_name.

Then use it to build 2 models: One using Price (Model-1) and one using Price_Log (Model-2).

In [689]:
def build_regression_model(df, target_variable, model_name):
    # Create X and y
    X = df.drop(target_variable, axis=1)
    y = df[target_variable]

    # Split the data into train and test sets
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=1)

    # Fit the linear regression model
    lin_reg_model = LinearRegression()
    lin_reg_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

    # Make predictions on the test set
    y_pred = lin_reg_model.predict(x_test)

    # Calculate performance metrics
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
    mask = y_test != 0 #excluding zero in y_test for MAPE calcuation
    mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_test[mask] - y_pred[mask]) / y_test[mask])) * 100

    # Calculate adjusted R-squared
    n = len(x_test)
    p = x_test.shape[1]
    adjusted_r2 = 1 - (1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - p - 1)

    # Create a DataFrame with the performance metrics
    performance_metrics = pd.DataFrame({
        'Metric': ['R2 Score', 'Mean Squared Error', 'Mean Absolute Error',
                   'Root Mean Squared Error', 'Mean Absolute Percentage Error', 'Adjusted R2'],
        'Value': [r2, mse, mae, rmse, mape, adjusted_r2]
    })

    # Round the performance metric values to 2 decimal places
    performance_metrics['Value'] = performance_metrics['Value'].round(2)

    print(f"Performance metrics for Linear Regression {model_name} using {target_variable}:")
    print(tabulate(performance_metrics, headers='keys', tablefmt='grid', showindex=False))

    return lin_reg_model

Model-2 using Price_Log as the target variable had much better performance metrics than Model-1 that used Price as the target variable.

The results of Model-2 are explained below:

R2 Score: The R2 score of 0.94 indicates that approximately 94% of the variance in the target variable is explained by the model. This implies that the model captures a significant amount of the variability in the data and provides a good fit.

Mean Squared Error (MSE): The MSE value of 0.05 represents the average squared difference between the predicted and actual values. A lower MSE indicates that, on average, the model's predictions are close to the actual values, suggesting good accuracy.

Mean Absolute Error (MAE): The MAE value of 0.16 represents the average absolute difference between the predicted and actual values. A lower MAE suggests that, on average, the model's predictions deviate by approximately 0.18 units from the actual values.

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): The RMSE value of 0.21 provides an interpretable measure of the average magnitude of the prediction errors in the same units as the target variable. A lower RMSE indicates smaller average prediction errors, suggesting good accuracy.

Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE): The MAPE is 16.45, which represents the average percentage difference between the predicted and actual values of 'Price_Log'.

Adjusted R2: The adjusted R2 value of 0.94 accounts for the number of predictors in the model. It suggests that the model's predictive power remains strong even after considering the number of predictors.

Overall, based on these metrics, the model demonstrates good performance with high R2 score, low MSE, MAE, RMSE and MAPE values. These results indicate that the model has a good fit to the data and provides accurate predictions.

Using Model-2, Cars4U will have a reliable model for predicting and calculating what price to use for their cars.

Perform a review of Model-2's Coefficients to view which features Impact Price both positively and negatively¶

- A Positive Coefficient means an increase in that Feature will increase the Price.

- A Negative Coefficient means an increase in that Feature will decrease the price.

In [692]:
p# Define a function to calculate and display the Positive and Negative Coefficients that impact the Price of used car.
def show_impact_features(df, target_variable, model_name):
    # Create X and y
    X = df.drop(target_variable, axis=1)
    y = df[target_variable]

    # Split the data into train and test sets
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=1)

    # Fit the linear regression model
    lin_reg_model = LinearRegression()
    lin_reg_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

    # Retrieve the feature coefficients and names
    feature_coefficients = lin_reg_model.coef_
    feature_names = X.columns

    # Create a DataFrame to store the feature coefficients and their impact
    feature_impact = pd.DataFrame({
        'Feature': feature_names,
        'Coefficient': feature_coefficients
    })

    # Sort the DataFrame by the absolute coefficients in descending order
    feature_impact = feature_impact.reindex(feature_impact['Coefficient'].abs().sort_values(ascending=False).index)
  
    # Split the DataFrame into positive and negative features
    pos = feature_impact[feature_impact['Coefficient'] > 0]  # Adjust the number to display more or fewer features
    neg = feature_impact[feature_impact['Coefficient'] < 0]  # Adjust the number to display more or fewer features
    
    # Sort positive features by feature name ascending
    pos = pos.sort_values('Coefficient', ascending=False)
    pos.rename(columns={'Coefficient': 'Pos Coef_'}, inplace=True)

    # Sort negative features by feature name ascending
    neg = neg.sort_values('Coefficient', ascending=True)
    neg.rename(columns={'Coefficient': 'Neg Coef_'}, inplace=True)

    # Create a combined DataFrame with positive and negative features side by side
    pos = pos[['Feature', 'Pos Coef_']].dropna().reset_index(drop=True)
    neg = neg[['Feature', 'Neg Coef_']].dropna().reset_index(drop=True)
    pos_neg_features = pd.concat([pos, neg], axis=1)

    return pos_neg_features

Guidance on which features to monitor when selecting used cars and the feature's impact on Price:¶

These features have a positive impact on Price:

  • Certain Brands (e.g. Lambo, Mini, Jaguar, Land-Rover, Mercedes, Audi, BMW)
  • Fuel_Type (Electric & Diesel)
  • Equivalent New Car Price of Same Car
  • Location (Bangalore, Hyderabad, Coimbatore Ahmedabad, Mumbai, and Chennai)
  • Auto Transmission
  • Higher Power bhp
  • Newer Year
  • Larger Engines CC
  • Owner Type (First)
  • More Seats

These features have a negative impact on Price:

  • Fuel_Type (CNG, Petrol, LPG)
  • Location (Kolkata, Delhi, Jaipur, Pune, and Kochi)
  • Certain Brands (e.g. Isuzu, Tata, Datsun, Ambassador, )
  • Manual Transmission
  • Older Years
  • Owner Type (2nd & 3rd)
